  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">No News is Bad News: Fragile Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">In Burundi, CAR, DR Congo, Mali and Somalia, FPU will focus on the development of alternative trusted channels of information and work in cooperation with civil society organizations on increased access to information, develop decentralized Internet connections for the public, enhance the sustainable capacity of local community and private radio stations. Lobby and advocacy will focus on human security and prevention of and reporting about gender based violence and increased accountability of the media to its audiences. Safety of media workers is a priority, cross-cutting goal of the program. Interventions and specific objectives per country are specified in the country profiles. It is our expectation that similar problems and topics of concern may come to the surface that are currently holding the first five countries back in achieving their potential. We particularly fear that the current conflict in Mali with pockets of terrorism in South Algeria, Northern Nigeria can or may lead to a collapse in Niger and Chad due to the inherent weak capacity of those states and the geographically position. e states. We hope that we will not have to move our attention to those countries but it is unfortunately more likely that we will.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Though the number of conflicts worldwide is shrinking, parts of Africa remain entangled in ethnic, religious and political strife. The absence of central government authority in countries such as DR Congo and the Central African Republic holds citizens hostage in militia-run regions without access to information and education, means to engage in economic development or decentralised systems for the rule of law or human security. In countries such as Mali, Somalia and Burundi, ethnic and regional dissent undermines economic growth and social cohesion. Large segments of the population are unable to access timely, accurate and trustworthy information. Women and youth are particularly under-served in national peace-building initiatives. In the absence of human security, women and youth are also victimised by gender-based violence and child soldier recruitment. Media and civil society advocacy groups are included in the approach in order to advocate for improved access to information. Innovation is needed to increase the access to digital information for local communities. FPU activities will also serve as a platform for dialogue and debate for local stakeholders with an emphasis on the participation of women and youth in the media, thus empowering them to become agents of change. In strong coordination with other international (media) development organisations, resilient structures will be developed to increase impact and added value of the international assistance programmes in the region.</narrative>
  </description>
